September 8 at 3:58 PM Â· Kings Mills, OH Â·

Kings Local School District, and especially Kings High School, we thank you for empowering us, supporting us, & getting behind us in every way possible to give us the chance to sing together again. post_text:
The Kings Varsity Football team will host the Winton Woods Warriors this Friday, August 28 to open their season!! Per the Governor's order, we have a 15% capacity limit at our stadium, and attendance is strictly limited to family members of our Band, Cheerleading, and Football programs.

There is NO public general admission permitted for our athletic events and no passes are accepted at Kings Varsity Football games. Viewing from outside Kings Stadium on campus (fence lines, parking lots, etc.) is not permitted.

GREAT NEWS!! Since we know many will not be able to attend, the Kings Athletic Department will be streaming LIVE this Friday! Subscribe to their YouTube channel watch the game live-streamed at https://youtu.be/HhpCWRKuqIc. You can also get live updates by following the Athletic Department on Twitter - @KingsAthletics.

We appreciate your cooperation and patience as we've worked through the guidelines and regulations.

An important update from Kings Athletics...

Looking forward to a safe and successful fall for all of our programs! We are waiting for the official order to come from the Governor's office and more requirements for hosting from the OHSAA on Wednesday.

In the meantime, it is important to note a few items. We will have a paperless and digital only ticket process. There will not be any purchase of tickets at the gate at any sporting event. Detailed information will be sent to all programs and parents this week.

Governor DeWine specifically addressed spectators today. We anticipate the order reiterating spectators will be restricted to family members of student-athletes and family members ofâ€¦

post_text: FYI-
shared_text:
Kings Athletic Department
August 12 at 6:18 PM Â·

As you are working towards selecting the best possible option for your student and/or student-athlete for the beginning of the school year, we wanted to be sure you had the correct information regarding athletic eligibility.

All students are eligible in regards to academic eligibility for the 1st quarter of 2020-2021. Students who are enrolled in the High School for 1st quarter 2020, whether in person, virtual, or a blended model are required to take and pass five one-credit courses or the equivalent to maintain eligibility for the 2nd grading period. Student-athletes in grades 7 and 8, are required to be passing four courses to maintain eligibility for the 2nd grading period.

If you have any questions or concerns regarding athletic eligibility, please do not hesitate to reach out to our department at 513-459-2937.

Go Knights!

post_text:
An email was sent to Kings families this morning with a draft of the district's Reopening plan for the 2020-2021 school year.

Important take-aways:
The plan contains two options for students: face-to-face instruction in Kings school buildings or distance learning through a third-party vendor.

Safety protocols are key to staff and students returning to -- and staying in -- our buildings safely. Safety protocols include health assessments, cleaning and disinfecting, social distancing, and the required wearing of face coverings.

Please take the time to review the plan and feel free to submit questions by using the link in the email.

During the last week in July, we will be asking parents to indicate which option they will choose for their students for the 20-21 school year. Additional information will be coming soon. Visit our website to view the plan - www.kingslocal.net.

post_text:
Congratulations to Kings High School 2020 graduate, Chelsey Zugaro who was named 2020 US Lacrosse Jackie Pitts Service Award Winner!

The Jackie Pitts Award The Jackie Pitts Award recognizes a senior player in each area who:
--Truly honors the game of lacrosse, is invested in the development of the game in her community,
--Is an exceptional player who continually strives to improve her game, and is an exemplary member of her team,
--Exemplifies the spirit of the game, on and off the field,
-- And academically, she is an outstanding student and a valued role model in her school.

Chelsey has given back to lacrosse in a number of ways...officiating, helping with clinics, and as an ambassador. She is also active in her community and school.

Congratulations, Chelsey! #KingsStrong

We are excited to announce that Kings Junior High School students, Addison Bays, Natalie DeVage, Claudia Ragsdale, and Michael Worthington, also known as The Four Musketeers, will compete at the National eCYBERMISSION competition this Friday, June 16.

Their project called "The Ghostbuster" is a biodegradable gill net. The students created The Ghostbuster to help with the global problem of â€œghost nets,â€ which are abandoned or lost fishing nets, causing death and destruction to ecosystems by endlessly trapping and killing marine life.

The team will be presenting their project virtually in a LIVE National Showcase that begins at 9:00 a.m. this Friday. Once the showcase is complete, voting will begin for the People's Choice Award.

Click on the image below to watch and VOTE for The Four Musketeers from Kings Mills, Ohio! Good luck Addison, Natalie, Claudia, and Michael! #KingsStrong

ROAD CLOSING:

Major construction has begun for a bridge rehabilitation project on state Route 48 at South Lebanon in Warren County, and the route is now closed.

S.R. 48 is closed over the Little Miami River, just south of its intersection with Mason-Morrow-Millgrove Road.

The closure will be in effect for up to 75 days, and while it is closed, thru-traffic motorists will be detoured by way of I-71, S.R. 123 and U.S. 22.

Beckett Springs is providing some free virtual support groups for adults interested and needing additional support coping through these difficult times. https://beckettsprings.com/coping-covid/

They are also offering summer therapeutic adolescent program for kids ages 5-18. This is a GREAT resource for families who have children that are struggling with mental health, behaviors, substance abuse, and more. They are adding optional extended days to their program to better support parents and their busy schedules this summer.

The program does accept Caresource and straight Ohio Medicaid, as well as a majority of all commercial insurance. In addition, they can also help with transportation.

post_text: Update from Kings Athletics
shared_text:
Kings Athletic Department
May 25 at 9:12 PM Â·

Knight Nation!

We hope you enjoyed a great holiday weekend and had a Happy Memorial Day!

With Governor DeWine announcing plans for sports/activities to resume this coming week, we have been working on plans to open our athletic facilities to the public and to get our athletic programs back together as soon as possible. With the announcement and updates coming on Thursday and Friday of last week, in addition to the holiday weekend, we still do not feel adequately prepared to reopen at this point.

Unfortunately, our stadium and athletic facilities will remain closed until we are completely ready to open for use. We appreciate your patience during this time and please know we are making plans to ensure the safety and security of all users when we reopen.

Once we feel comfortable with our plans for use and decide to open facilities, we will make sure to update the community as soon as possible.

If you have specific questions please do not hesitate to contact our office directly at 513-459-2937.

Go Knights!

Kings Local School District

post_text:
Today we remember those who died to allow us our freedom. ğŸ‡ºğŸ‡¸

Did you know?
Originally Memorial Day was known as Decoration Day, meant to honor the Union and the Confederate soldiers who died during the American Civil War. By the 1900s it had become a day to celebrate all American soldiers who died while serving in the military. It wasn't until 1967 that it was legally named Memorial Day.

ROAD REPAIR UPDATE:

The Ohio Department of Transportation has a project going on that will likely affect our community. A bridge project on state Route 48 at South Lebanon where contractors for the Ohio Department of Transportation will be rehabilitating the structure over the Little Miami River.

Since the start of the project, crews have installed a work platform to be used during construction, and additional site preparations will continue early next week. Single-lane restrictions will be in effect again on Monday, May 18, and traffic will be maintained by flaggers from approximately 9 a.m. to 3:30 p.m.

Following preliminary site work, the bridge will be closed at the Little Miamiâ€¦

post_text: Congratulations to the Class of 2020 Scholar Athletes! Twenty-eight student-athletes qualified for the prestigious honor! Check out the video below. Also, head over the Kings Athletic Department Facebook page to see our scholar-athletes receive their gifts today!
shared_text:

2020 Senior Scholar-Athletes

Kings Athletic Department
May 13 at 4:08 PM Â·

Today marked the 25th Anniversary of the Senior Scholar-Athlete Luncheon. We are disappointed we couldn't hold our luncheon as normal but we were excited to be able to visit our 28 senior student-athletes to honor and recognize them today!

In order to achieve this award, our Senior athletes must have had a GPA of 3.850 or above, achieved 4 Varsity Letters in one sport, or 5 or more Varsity Letters in multiple programs. We are very proud of their accomplishments and congratulations to all!

Check out the 2020 Senior-Scholar picture album from our visits today and a special video we produced for our seniors, below! #2020ScholarAthletes

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2jfie9YFRGo

MARK YOUR CALENDARS!

The Kings Athletic Department has partnered with the 2nd & 7 Foundation to encourage reading and developing leaders. Kings High School student-athletes have been visiting our elementary schools to read to students a book provided by the 2nd & 7 Foundation. Each child is provided a free book.

Because of COVID-19, our student-athletes weren't able to visit the schools, so young readers are invited to join in for a Facebook Live reading of "The Hog Mollies & Little Lily's Legacy" on Tuesday, May 5th at 1pm, by the Foundation Co-Founder, Ryan Miller.

JOIN US TUESDAY MAY 5 AT 1PM EST!
With a special Hog Mollie appearance the kids will love!
Facebook Live! - 2nd & 7 Foundation

Students can read along on the digital copy of this story at: https://kids.secondandseven.com/

It's School Bus Driver Appreciation Day in Ohio. There are 20,000 school bus drivers in Ohio who transport more than 800,000 kids.

We are so lucky to have the best bus drivers at Kings! It's not an easy job. It can be chaotic and stressful, but our bus drivers play a vital role in the educational process.

Please take a moment to thank the men and women who work in our Transportation Department for their dedication to keeping our children safe each day! #KingsStrong Petermann Bus

Yesterday, Governor Mike DeWine announced that a new toll-free emotional support call service, the COVID CareLine, has been created by the Ohio Dept of Mental Health and Addiction. It will be open from 8am to 8pm, 7 days/week. (Calls after those hours will roll over to the national suicide hotline.)

Trained responders will be on the line to support and assist all Ohioans who are struggling with the impacts of the pandemic. This COVID CareLine can be reached at 800-720-9616.

All calls are handled by licensed mental health counselors & social workers and are completely confidential. They can listen, help with some screenings, and connect callers to local resources in their communities they may need.

post_text: After yesterday's announcement from Governor Mike DeWine about not going back to school in our buildings, an extreme sense of sadness was felt among ALL of our staff; that includes, teachers, paras, cafeteria workers, custodians, bus drivers, technology techs, secretaries, and administrators. ALL of our staff. We miss (y)our students and can't wait for our hallways and classrooms to be filled with the sounds of lockers slamming, pencils being sharpened, chairs scooting across the floor, computers whirring, kitchen pans clanging, buses idling, bells ringing, students laughing, and all of us to be learning together once again! We. Miss. You. #KingsStrong, always.

Contractors for the Ohio Department of Transportation will be rehabilitating the structure on state Route 48 over the Little Miami near the corporation limit of South Lebanon.

Preliminary work is scheduled to begin the week of April 20, with crews prepping the site and staging equipment and materials. S.R. 48 will be subject to short-term lane restrictions on the bridge from 8 a.m. to 3 p.m. daily through the end of May, and traffic will be maintained by flaggers.

Following initial work, the bridge will be closed beginning Monday, June 1. The closure will be in effect for up to 75 days, and motorists will be detoured by way of I-71, S.R. 123 and U.S. 22.

Learn more by clicking below.

Two weeks from today, on Tuesday, April 28, the Ohio Primary Election will take place.

Ohio Governor, Mike DeWine signed House Bill (HB) 197 into law that addressed the change of date of the 2020 Primary Election due to COVID-19.

The bill set the date for the 2020 Primary Election from March 17 to April 28, 2020. There will be NO in-person voting for the primary election. The only way to vote is by absentee.

The deadline to request a ballot is noon on April 25. Ballots themselves should arrive accompanied by a postage-paid envelope. Fill out the ballot and drop it in the mail, or take it to a dropbox at your county board of elections. Ballots must be postmarked by April 27.

Kings has an important issue on the ballot. A 4.7 mill bond issue will fund building and reconstruction of some of our school buildings to accommodate the overcapacity of current enrollment and the future predicted enrollment increases. Learn more at www.kingsfacilities.org.

It is with great sadness that the Kings Football Program had to cancel their annual Mulch Sale.

For 26 years, the KFB Program has sold mulch to the Kings Community in what is one of their largest fundraisers of the year. The mulch sale fundraiser generates over 50% of operating costs (equipment, staffing, uniforms, etc.) Approximately $2 for every bag sold is profit for the program. Head Coach, Alex Garvin said, "We are definitely disappointed. We know our community looks forward to our players delivering their mulch every year, and on a lighter note, delivery days help keep our players in shape!" Garvin noted that they will be back delivering again in 2021, but are hopeful that theâ€¦ More

We know our community looks forward to our players delivering their mulch every year, and on a lighter note, delivery days help keep our players in shape!" Garvin noted that they will be back delivering again in 2021, but are hopeful that theâ€¦ More

We are all looking for good news during these uncertain times. Well, we have some to share!!!

We just found out that the Kings Local School District is among only 754 school districts in the country that are among the Best Communities in the nation for music education named by NAMM Foundation! This is the 4th YEAR IN A ROW that Kings has received this designation!

The award program recognizes outstanding efforts by teachers, administrators, parents, students and community leaders who have made music education part of a well-rounded education. Designations are made to districts and schools that demonstrate an exceptionally high commitment and access to music education.

Congratulations to all of our Kings music educators for making a difference in our studentsâ€™ lives and bringing beautiful music into ours! #KingsStrong

Governor Mike DeWine signed HB 197 into law on Friday that sets the 2020 Ohio Primary election to April 28. There will be NO in-person voting. The only way to vote is by absentee. If you didnâ€™t vote early or absentee prior to March 17, click the link below to request an absentee ballot. The deadline to request a ballot is noon on April 25.

Ballots themselves should arrive accompanied by a postage-paid envelope. Fill out the ballot and drop it in the mail, or take it to a dropbox at your county board of elections. Ballots must be postmarked by April 27.

post_text:
Dear Parent/Guardians,

We would like to thank you for your patience as we attempt to feed our children, plan to educate our children from home if we have to move to online learning, and do our best to make sure everyone is safe.

We are working behind the scenes diligently to try to make this happen. We know this is a very difficult time for all of us. Please be patient with us. We will give you more information as we have it.

We THANK YOU for sticking with us through this unprecedented journey. We know your lives have been turned upside-down with lots of unknowns. WE salute you! Hang in there! We ARE #KingsStrong!

post_text:
Looking for an activity for after dinner or anytime?

Miss Danielle from Kings Kids at SLE, and her son Noah made this great video of a Floating Stickman!

What you will need:
- water
- dry erase markers
- dish

Why does this work?

The ink in dry erase markers is insoluble. When you pour water onto a dry erase stick figure on a smooth surface, a strong buoyancy force overcomes the stickiness of the ink, pulling the stick figure off the surface and causing it magically float on the water.

Watch â€”-> https://tinyurl.com/stjq9a5

Kings has an important issue on the ballot on Tuesday. A 4.7 mill bond issue will support Kings Master Facilities Plan to accommodate the increased growth of over 600 students in the last 5 years. Projections show another 500-700 students will enroll by the 2023-2024 school year.

Currently, 4 out of 6 of our school buildings have NO AVAILABLE CLASSROOMS.

There are 2 more opportunities for early voting. The Warren County Board of Elections is open today until 5pm and Monday from 8am until 2pm. If you have an absentee ballot, you can put it in the drop box at the BOE.

On Thursday Governor Mike DeWine announced that all Ohio public schools would be closed for three weeks. Many Ohio students depend on their local schools for free and reduced school breakfast and lunches throughout the school year. The sudden and unexpected nature of this cancellation leaves many families struggling to find resources for food. Additionally, many low-income workers do not have benefits that pay them for work when their place of employment has closed temporarily.

Joshuaâ€™s Place is partnering with local school districts in Kingâ€™s, Mason, Lebanon and Little Miami to help these students have food while school is out. The focus of this plan is to collect, package and distributeâ€¦

Did you know? Today is Holi Festival 2020!

Holi is considered as one of the most revered and celebrated festivals of India and it is celebrated in almost every part of the country. It is also sometimes called the â€œfestival of loveâ€ or the "festival of colors" as on this day people get to unite together forgetting all resentments and all types of bad feelings towards each other. People come out on the streets to play with colors, and drench each other in colored water through water guns or balloons.

Holi is a popular ancient Indian festival, originating from the Indian subcontinent. It is celebrated predominantly in India, but has also spread to other areas of Asia and parts of the Western world through the diaspora from the Indian subcontinent.

As concerns grow around the coronavirus, Secretary of State Frank LaRose held a press conference to recommend that Ohioans strongly consider voting early. The Warren County Board of Elections has extended their early voting hours to accommodate his recommendation.They are open this week, through Friday from 8am-7pm, Saturday 8am-4pm and Sunday from 1-5pm.

You can still request an absentee ballot but it must be postmarked by March 16. Another option is to request an absentee and drop it off at the Board of Elections on Election Day, March 17. There will be curbside drop-off available at the county board.

Throughout the next five years, Congress continued to pass joint resolutions designating a week in March as â€œWomenâ€™s History Week.â€ In 1987 after being petitioned by the National Womenâ€™s History Project, Congress passed Pub. The March 17 Primary Election will have a 4.7 mill bond issue on the ballot for Kings. This bond issue, if passed, will cost the Kings taxpayer $13.75/month for every $100,000 of true property value.

The bond issue will help the District accommodate the enrollment growth of over 600 students in the last 5 years and the projected 600 more to come by the 2023-2024 school year.

Currently, 4 out of 6 of our school buildings are over capacity. Learn more about the bond issue and facilities master plan at www.kingsfacilities.org.

It's that time of year...Nerf Wars are back!

We have been informed by our School Resource Officers that the annual Nerf Wars are in full swing throughout our community.

Nerf Wars (aka: dart wars) is a friendly game that involve teenagers, ordinarily far past the point of playing with toys, stock up on Nerf guns, hoard foam darts and plot elaborate strategies against their classmates.

As in years past, we want to share these simple reminders to those participating in this activity:

DO NOT carry a Nerf gun that is all-black! Ensure your Nerf gun is easily identifiable as a â€œtoy gunâ€ & is primarily painted with fluorescent colors: bright orange, bright green, bright pink, etc;

DO NOTâ€¦

post_text: Lots of top-ten finishes at the STATE Swim Meet. We are so proud of our Aqua Knights! What a great season! Good luck, Seniors! #KingsStrong
shared_text:
Kings KABC
February 25 at 4:36 PM Â·

Congrats, Aqua Knights on an amazing weekend at the OHSAA State Championships! Senior Leah Luckett capped off a great career by placing 9th in the 200 yard freestyle and 6th in the 100 yard freestyle! Several other Knights claimed top-ten state finishes! Jake Young finished 8th in the 200 yard IM and Kevin Glennon finished 5th in the 100 yard butterfly! The Men's 200 yard medley relay of Kevin Glennon, Jake Young, Aiden Leamer, and Kavin Lynch finished 6th overall and set a new school record! Today during In-Service Day, our Kings staff participated in a 2 1/2 hour Cost of Poverty Experience (COPE). The simulation created by Think Tank, Inc., takes participants through a simulated month in the life of a family experiencing poverty. Kings teachers, counselors, and administrators invested time during their inservice day to better understand families in our community.

The simulation gave a brief glimpse into the feelings, experiences, stresses, and bonds that so many families experience while dealing with poverty. It is also extremely insightful into the guilt and destruction of self esteem accompanying not always being able to help improve oneâ€™s own situation.

This is just another example of how we, as a District, are committed to making diversity and inclusion a priority.

We are thankful to Joshua's Place for sponsoring the event and all of volunteers who served and those who financially support Joshuaâ€™s Place to make this day possible.

You can learn more about the the COPE simulation here:

https://thinktank-inc.org/cope

post_text: Sounds like something fun to do tonight with the family! Hope to see you there! #KingsStrong #relate
shared_text:
Kings Basketball Association (KBA)
February 12 at 12:27 PM Â·

KBA Families,

The Kings 7th grade boys team is playing in the ECC Tournament Championship at KHS this evening at 5:30. This group of boys is trying to finish off their undefeated season and bring the trophy home to Kings. I know the team would love the extra support if your family is free this evening to come watch. This could also be a great for the kids in our program to see what things will be like for them in the not so distant future as well.

Let's pack The Castle! Go Knights!

KBA Board

Some are questioning the Kings District about whether we are really overcrowded and overcapacity.

Let us show you a few examples below. The first is a Spanish class at KHS, orchestra class on the stage at CIS, Band class in the Teacherâ€™s Lounge at CIS, and 63 students in Choir class at CIS.

The 4.7 mill bond issue will help us relieve the overcrowded conditions in our buildings. Election Day is 5 weeks from today. Are you registered? Have you applied for an absentee ballot? The deadline to register to vote is February 18. Early voting begins on February 19. Learn more about voting - https://kingsfacilities.org/vote/

post_text:
If the 4.7 mill bond issue on the March 17 ballot doesn't pass, and as enrollment continues to rise as projected, class sizes will become larger, more mobile classrooms will be needed, and all-day kindergarten will need to be re-evaluated.

Where our children learn and our staff teach matters!

Learn more about the bond and the Master Facilities Plan at www.kingsfacilities.org.
shared_text:
Kings Local School Master Facilities Plan
Overcapacity Buildings4 out of 6 of our school buildings are either at or over design capacity based on the Ohio Facilities Construction Commission (OFCC) standards. Two others are very close to being at capacity. In fact, Kings High School enrollment is already 40% over capacity.

The Warren County Imagination Library is here! Kings Local School District is excited to be a partner in this county-wide effort with the goal that Every Child Reads Every Day!

All Warren County children under five can have a FREE book mailed to THEM every month. Sign up now at www.imaginationlibrary.org

Warren County Imagination Library Founding Partners are Franklin-Springboro Public Library, Lebanon Public Library, Mary L. Cook Public Library, Mason Public Library, Salem Township Public Library, United Way of Warren County, and Warren County Foundation. The five libraries have generously funded a three-year pilot in collaboration with the Ohio Governorâ€™s Imagination Library and Dolly Partonâ€™s Imagination Library.

Please sign up, share this post and join us in The Biggest Civic Engagement in Warren County History â€“ A Generational Change! Questions? Contact the Warren County Imagination Library at 513-934-1001 or info@warrencountyfoundation.org

post_text:
While many of our students were still sleeping and enjoying a snow day last Friday, four Kings High School students attended the Greater Cincinnati Leadership & Ethics Seminar sponsored by the West Point Society of Greater Cincinnati.

This is the 8th year of the event and they had 261 students registered from almost 100 different schools. In all, the event consists of over 400 students, faculty, and volunteers.

Pictured from L-R: KHS teacher, Nick Molz, Davis Wik, Christian Stacy, Spencer Wind, and Kiley Ingram.
